    think='Let me analyze what I\'ve found so far:\n\n1. **Blocking Issue - BDD 
Step Definition Duplication**: \n   - There are already 4 existing matching step
definition files that cover the same scenarios in `matching.feature`.\n   - The 
PR adds a new consolidated `matching.steps.js` that covers ALL scenarios in the 
feature file.\n   - Jest config uses `testMatch: [\'<rootDir>/tests/bdd/step-def
initions/*.steps.js\']` which will match BOTH the old individual files AND the n
ew consolidated file.\n   - This means jest-cucumber will try to define the same
feature multiple times with different step definitions, which will cause conflic
ts or duplicate test execution.\n   - **This is Blocking** because it will break
the BDD test suite.\n\n2. **Major Issue - matching_bloc_test.dart uses hardcoded
strings instead of constants**:\n   - The PR refactored `matching_bloc.dart` to 
use `kNetworkErrorMessage` constant.\n   - But `matching_bloc_test.dart` still u
ses hardcoded `\'网络异常，请检查连接后重试\'` and `\'请先完善个人资料\'` string
s.\n   - The tests should be updated to use the same constants to ensure they st
ay in sync.\n   - Actually wait, `matching_bloc_test.dart` was NOT modified in t
his PR. But since `matching_bloc.dart` was changed to use constants, and the tes
t still uses hardcoded strings... let me check if the test still passes. The tes
t asserts on `MatchingFailure` with message `\'网络异常，请检查连接后重试\'`, an
d the bloc now emits `MatchingFailure(kNetworkErrorMessage)` where `kNetworkErro
rMessage = \'网络异常，请检查连接后重试\'`. So the test should still pass becaus
e the value is the same. But from a maintenance perspective, the test should use
the constant too. This is a Minor issue at most, or maybe Major for maintainabil
ity.\n\nWait, actually looking at the diff again, `matching_bloc_test.dart` is N
OT in the diff. It wasn\'t changed. The tests still pass because the string valu
es are the same. But ideally tests should import and use constants.\n\n3. **Mino
r Issue - BDD test for profile incomplete is weak**:\n   - The step definition a
ccepts `code === 0` or `404` as valid when testing profile incomplete blocking, 
with a comment explaining that the Guard is mocked.\n   - This means the test do
esn\'t actually verify the blocking behavior - it\'s just documenting the limita
tion.\n   - According to the PRD (v1-profile.md), `ProfileCompletionGuard` shoul
d return `code=1000`.\n   - In the bdd-setup.js, `ProfileCompletionGuard` is ove
rridden with `canActivate: () => true`, so the guard is completely bypassed.\n  
- The test accepts this and even accepts `code === 0` as valid. This makes the B
DD test meaningless for this scenario.\n   - However, this is more of a test inf
rastructure limitation than a code bug.\n\n4. **Code Style - Constant naming**:\
n   - `readability.md` says constants should use `maxSwipeCount` style (camelCas
e), not `MAX_SWIPE` or `kMaxSwipeCount`.\n   - The PR uses `kProfileIncompleteCo
de`, `kProfileIncompleteMessage`, `kNetworkErrorMessage`.\n   - The `k` prefix i
s a Flutter convention (from the Flutter framework itself, e.g., `kDebugMode`), 
but `readability.md` says to use `maxSwipeCount` style which implies camelCase w
ithout prefix.\n   - Actually, looking at the readability.md more carefully: "常
量: `maxSwipeCount` | `MAX_SWIPE`（全大写 Agent 易混淆）". It doesn\'t mention `
k` prefix. The `k` prefix is a common Flutter/Dart convention, but the project s
pec says camelCase without prefix. This is a Minor issue.\n\n5. **Documentation*
*:\n   - The PR updates `docs/modules/matching.md` which is good.\n   - But I sh
ould check if `docs/api/matching.md` or `docs/api/socket-events.md` were updated
too. According to `.doc-coverage.txt`, these files exist in the PR. But the diff
only showed changes to `docs/modules/matching.md`. Let me verify.\n\nActually, l
ooking at the diff output again:\n```\n docs/modules/matching.md                
          |   6 +-\n tests/bdd/matching.feature                         |   6 +\
n tests/bdd/step-definitions/matching.steps.js       | 560 +++++++++++++++++++++
\n 9 files changed, 762 insertions(+), 11 deletions(-)\n```\n\nOnly `docs/module
s/matching.md` was changed among docs. The `.doc-coverage.txt` shows all files i
n the PR branch, not just changed ones.\n\n6. **Missing Maestro E2E updates**:\n
  - The PR changes error handling in the matching flow (profile incomplete).\n  
- According to `testing.md`, Maestro E2E is required for "用户可见的核心页面/流
程".\n   - However, this PR doesn\'t change any UI widgets or pages - it only re
factors repository/bloc layer constants. So Maestro updates are likely not neede
d.\n\n7. **Test Coverage**:\n   - Added `match_list_cubit_test.dart` - good cove
rage for MatchListCubit.\n   - But `matching_bloc_test.dart` still uses hardcode
d strings. Not a functional issue but maintenance issue.\n   - The BDD step defi
nitions file is problematic due to duplication.\n\nLet me verify the BDD duplica
tion issue more carefully. I\'ll check if jest-cucumber actually has a problem w
ith multiple step definition files for the same feature.\n\nLooking at jest-cucu
mber documentation: each `.steps.js` file calls `defineFeature(feature, ...)` wh
ich registers the feature. If multiple files call `defineFeature` with the same 
feature, jest-cucumber will run all of them. However, if they define the same sc
enarios, it would be duplicate tests, not necessarily failures.\n\nBUT, there\'s
a subtle issue: if the existing individual step definition files and the new con
solidated file both import and define steps for the same feature, Jest will run 
both. The existing files might have slightly different step definitions. Let me 
check one of the existing files to see if they conflict.\n\nActually, looking at
the `.doc-coverage.txt`, the existing step definition files are:\n- `matching_ca
rd_recommendations.steps.js`\n- `matching_match_list.steps.js`\n- `matching_mutu
al_like_creates_match.steps.js`\n- `matching_swipe_actions.steps.js`\n\nAnd the 
PR adds:\n- `matching.steps.js`\n\nThe jest config matches ALL `*.steps.js` file
s. So ALL of these will be executed. The new `matching.steps.js` loads the SAME 
`matching.feature` file and defines steps for ALL scenarios. The existing files 
each load the same feature and define steps for subsets of scenarios.\n\nIn jest
-cucumber, when you call `defineFeature(feature, test => { test(\'Scenario Name\
', ...) })`, it registers a Jest test for each scenario. If multiple step defini
tion files register tests for the same feature, Jest will run all of them. This 
is actually supported by jest-cucumber - you can split step definitions across m
ultiple files.\n\nHowever, there\'s a problem: the existing files and the new fi
